@node "Features" "Features"
@toc "Contents"
@next "Introduction"
@prev "Disclaimer"

     - -- 3. Features ]----.
 - -- --- -----------------'

o  Reads CNet's selectlist and creates Hydra sendlist

o  Transfers  run  over  a  temporary dir - no orphan files in any subboard
   when transfer gets interrupted!

o  Fully  aware of *ALL* influences on transfer, such as byte/file credits;
   daily bytes/files; disabled ratios; etc.

o  Analyses Hydra's result-log for filenames & sizes

o  Adds uploaded files into CNet's dirlisting; files are online immediately
   after successful transfer! 

o  Describes uploaded files the normal way, thus you can use your preferred
   File_ID.diz processor or whatever! 

o  Sysop only must move files from tempdir to the final location 

o  Gives correct upload credits depending on users ratio  

o  Updates _Items3 datafile for correct file/credit manipulation 

o  Writes CNet conform into the up/download logfile 

o  Fully aware  of  carrier  losses  &  resumable files; writes automail &
   prompts user for upload resume! 

o  utterly  easy installation, needs very few configuration; only 2 changes
   to  your  bbstext,  1  extra subboard, 1 change in the main program, and
   you're ready to burn something! 

o  Localized.  Multiple language output possible!   

o  Fully  multiline aware, gets the devicename and unitnumber of the serial
   from CNet's main configuration. 

o  Optionally increases file's download counter 

o  Can cope with read only media (CD-Temp aware) 

o  deactives yet don't purges waiting OLM's during transfer
@endnode

@node "Introduction" "Introduction"
@toc "Contents"
@next "AboutHydra"
@prev "Features"

     - -- 4.1. Introduction ]----.
 - -- --- -----------------------'

Maybe  you've heard about that Hydra-thingie and the things it does before,
but  because  your  beloved BBS program (namely CNet ;) doesn't support it,
you never got in touch with it.  Until now...
@endnode

@node "AboutHydra" "What is Hydra?!"
@toc "Contents"
@next "TheoryOperation"
@prev "Introduction"

     - -- 4.2. What is Hydra?! ]----.
 - -- --- --------------------------'

Hydra  (or  Hydracom)  is  a  bi-directional  protocol.  You can upload and
download  at  the  same  time,  without any noticable loss on the CPS side.
While you are transferring data, you also can chat with the remote side.
@endnode

@node "TheoryOperation" "Theory of Operation"
@toc "Contents"
@next "NeedfulThings"
@prev "AboutHydra"

     - -- 4.3. Theory of Operation ]----.
 - -- --- ------------------------------'

First,  the  Selectlist of CNet has to be translated into a Hydra sendlist,
and it also has to be "parsed" to find all the values for deducting credits
and all that stuff.

Second,  Hydra  is  invoked  (this is the easiest part of the job), and the
items  in  the  sendlist  will be transferred to the user while at the same
time he can upload something.

Third,  the  received  files will be moved into the corresponding dirs, and
will  be @{b}completely@{ub} processed.  That is:  putting them into CNet's dirlist,
giving  credits  to  uploader,  manipulating _items3 datafile, checking for
unfinished files, and bringing CNet back to life :) ...
@endnode

@node "NeedfulThings" "Needful Things"
@toc "Contents"
@next "Installation"
@prev "TheoryOperation"

     - -- 5.1. Needful Things ]----.
 - -- --- -------------------------'

- You need the following files in C: or somewhere else in your path:
  * Copy
  * Delete
  * Move        (submitted, as this is no standard command)
  * Hydracom    (not submitted; try to get the file termXX-extras.lha
                on Aminet (comm/term), which contains the actual
                revision of Hydracom by Olaf Barthel.)

- You have to run @{u}every port@{uu} you want to use Hydra with in shared mode

- Hydra/3 uses CNet's OLM temp (as stated in Config/Paths) as his temporary
  Dir. This should reside somewhere in RAM:

- It  also  uses  "CONFIG/Paths/CD-ROM U/D temp" for xfers from CD-ROMs (or
  other  read-only  media in general).  Make sure this leads to an location
  with  enough  space left (default is 'RAM:', but this might be hazardous,
  especially when You are low on Memory).
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"
@toc "Contents"
@next "Configuration"
@prev "NeedfulThings"

     - -- 5.2. Installation ]----.
 - -- --- -----------------------'

- @{fg highlight}^Q@{fg text} means CTRL-Q and @{fg shine}^Y@{fg text} means CTRL-Y


- Copy all *.rexx files to 'Pfiles:Hydra3/'


- Edit  CNet:bbsmenu<n>.  Add  the  following  new commands below all other
  commands in the "4; ud/base" menu:

  <TAB>HYdra     <TAB>|@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}#0Pfiles:Hydra3/Hydra3-Main.rexx}|
  <TAB>SETALLBACK<TAB>|@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}#0Pfiles:Hydra3/Hydra3-Post.rexx}|


- Edit  CNet:bbstext<n>,  and  change the following lines (take care of not
  adding more lines than there were before!)

  Line 80: @{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}n1Lost carrier.@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}1@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}#0 Pfiles:Hydra3/Hydra3-Lost.rexx}
           
  Add to Line 394: @{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}t68 #163}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}JN1}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}#0Pfiles:Hydra3/Hydra3-Adds.rexx}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}1}
  e.g. in the original bbstext:

@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}n1@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}q0@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}c6(@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}c7@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}v48}@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}c6)@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}c7 @{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}v49}> @{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}q1@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}t68 #163}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}JN1}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}#0Pfiles:Hydra3/Hydra3-Adds.rexx}@{fg shine}^Q@{fg text}1}


- Now set up an new Subboard escpecially for Hydra-Transfers.
  ATTENTION: The  Direcory (on Disk) @{b}MUST NOT@{ub} be "UDbase<n>:Hydra", as this
  dir will be created automagically from the script as temp receive path!
  It  also  must  reside on @{u}one@{uu} UDbase-partition and may not be spread over
  more!

  The following entries are used by Hydra/3 directly:

  Upload file ratio#   (to determine which credit-ratio to use from the
  Upload file ratio#                                   user's account.)

  Upload time return % (set this to 0 if You don't like this.  At  default,
                        100% of the time used for upload will be  added  to
                        the users onlinetime.  Note  that  the  added  time
                        depends on how much the user uploads,  not  on  the
                        time needed for the whole transfer.)
@endnode

@node "Configuration" "Configuration"
@toc "Contents"
@next "Updating"
@prev "Installation"

     - -- 5.3. Configuration: ]----.
 - -- --- -------------------------'


@{b}@{u}The Config-File "Hydra3.cfg":@{ub}@{uu}

Here you can configure the main-options you have to configurate for sure to
run Hydra.  The "Defaults" are set here as examples.

These are:

// Title of the UL-Tmp-Dir
@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}z1[ HYDRA-TRANSFER!! ]@{fg shine}^Y@{fg text}z0

This  is  the  title  of  the Hydra-Transfer-Subboard.  Needed to recognize
wether  or  not  the  user  is in the correct location for hydra transfers.
Note that it HAS to be the complete name, including MCI-Codes you might use
to especially highlight this subboard in the list.  (Note:  it would NOT be
absolutely  necessary  to receive files into this special subdirectory, but
as it speeds up things A LOT when processing a [nearly] empty directory, we
decided to implement it this way.) (Remember: @{fg shine}^Q@{fg text} means CTRL-Q and @{fg shine}^Y@{fg text} means
CTRL-Y !)


// In which UDbase does the Hydra-Subboard reside? (0-21)
0

Because  there  is  no  propper way to determine in which UDbase your newly
created  subboard resides (at least we haven't found it, this was btw.  the
reason  why v0.15b crashed on some multiline systems), you have to enter on
which  UDbase-Partition your Hydra-Dir (not the data or something else) is.
Usually, this will be UDbase0:


// increase Dloads by one: 1=Yes; 0=No
1

The  number  of downloads are increased in the filelist, when IncDL ist set
to 1.  But beware:  It can take quite a while updating huge filelists!  The
entiry _items3 has to be read, parsed and searched for the matching entries
from  EVERY subboard the user downloaded a file from!  ARexx IS pretty slow
for  this!   Hint:   This  function  will  be  significantly faster if your
heavily frequented subboards are RRed from time to time!


// writing to Logs: 1=Yes; 0=No
1

Because  of a strange bug you can deactivate writing to the CNet xfer-logs.
If  Errors  occur  especially  and  quite  often  in  line  449 or 459 then
deactivate   this!    (Meanwhile   we   assume   this   is  a  bug  in  the
Arexx-interpreter itself.)



@{b}@{u}Explanation of Config in "Hydra3-Main.rexx":@{ub}@{uu}

You may have to change the script itself, depending on how your CNet is set
up.  Just look through it, if there are some things are not set the way you
need.   You  maybe  want  to  edit  the multilanguage config as well.  When
translating,  we  were  assuming  that  you  use  "0",  english, as default
language.   "1"  is  provided  as  a  german  text.  You may add/change the
translation for your personal needs.

aocom="AO"                      /* BBSCommand for "Adopt Orphans"       */
wrcom="wr"                      /* BBSCommand for "Write" Description   */

BBScommands.  May differ in your enviroment, so edit if necessary.

hststring="HST"                        /* used for HST-Check */

Its  doesn't  make  much sense using Hydra with the USR HST-protocol, since
HST is an unidirectional protocol and Hydra is bidirectional.  Hydra should
switch  to unidirectional transfer when invoked on a HST connection, but we
did NOT test this.  Therefore, we provided a check for this, which tries to
find the HST keyword in the connect-string.  If successful, the script will
be  aborted.   Just  ignore  this  if your modem(s) don't support HST.  HST
users  should use ZModem instead, anyway.  Or better:  update to some up to
date modem!  :)

newname.0="new"                 /* Show "New" - Language 0              */
newname.1="neu"                 /* Show "New" - Language 1              */

In some languages, "New" may be called otherwise.



@{b}@{u}Explanation of Config in "Hydra3-Post.rexx" and "Hydra3-Lost.rexx":@{ub}@{uu}

Just edit the multilanguage config, if needed!



Nothing to change in "Hydra3-Adds.rexx" ;)
@endnode

@node "Updating" "Updating from V0.15"
@toc "Contents"
@next "HowToUseIt"
@prev "Configuration"

    - -- 10. If You are updating from V0.15: ]----.
 - -- --------------------------------------------'


Some of the most important settings are now put into a @{" Config-File " link "Configuration" 5}.  Two
new options are explained there as well.

A  @{" new check " link "Configuration" 70}  is introduced, which aborts the script, if a HST-connected
user tries to use Hydra.

Hydra/3  supports  the CD-Temp-Flag when set in selected files.  These files
will  be  copied  to  the destination as stated in CONFIG/Paths/"CD-ROM U/D
temp".   Default  (in  CONFIG) is "RAM:".  Maybe you should set this to any
other location if you are low on memory.

BTW: There is nothing to change in BBStext and BBSmenu.

@{u}New Variables in Multilanguage Config@{uu}

Main-Unit:   hstcon,  readselect,  compcom,  movdel,  move, Delete, Update,
             CDcopy, complete, Yes, No

Lost-Unit:   fin

Post-Unit:   Offcom, logoff


For more information about this update see the @{" History " link "History" 0} !
@endnode

@node "HowToUseIt" "How to use it"
@toc "Contents"
@next "HowToUsersUseIt"
@prev "Updating"

     - -- 6.1. How to use it... ]----.
 - -- --- ---------------------------'

Things  are pretty easy for your users once you have successfully installed
the program.  They may type "HYdra" at any subboard command prompt.  If the
user is not in the correct subboard, he will be prompted to enter the Hydra
transfer  subboard.  If the user is in the correct subboard, the selectlist
will  be processed, and it ends up in a prompt were the user is asked if he
is  sure to start the transfer.  At this point, it depends on what terminal
software  your  user  has and how Hydra is implemented on HIS end.  On YOUR
side, after pressing CR/Y HydraCom will be invoked and you're ready to go.
@endnode

@node "HowToUsersUseIt" "How to let your users use it"
@toc "Contents"
@next "History"
@prev "HowToUseIt"

     - -- 6.2. How to let your users use it ]----.
 - -- --- ---------------------------------------'

Depending  on  the  terminal  software  your user runs, there are different
solutions  for  the  Hydra  task.  We know of at least 2 solutions for each
NComm,  Term,  and  Terminus.  The cornerstone is that the terminal must be
able  to open the serial.device in shared mode.  Almost every BBS had those
Hydra installation packets for each and every terminal a few month ago when
the big Hydra run on the Amiga started.  Look there for any solutions.  One
of the best might be to use the new "transfer" settings from Term 4.3a on.
@endnode

@node "History" "History"
@toc "Contents"
@next "GetInTouch"
@prev "HowToUsersUseIt"

     - -- 7. History ]----.
 - -- --- ----------------'

V0.0 - V0.14    Internal revisions for beta-testing-purposes only


V0.15 beta      Initial release to the Public

(Why  beta?   Because  we were not able to test it on some system with more
than one port.  But it should work, as far as we can see...)

(it did not always, as we know now! :))

V0.16 - V0.xx   Internal revisions for beta-testing-purposes only


V0.xx           Changes since V0.15beta:

@{u}* Known Bugs:@{uu}

-  The Main-script aborts sometimes with an error, pointing to a line which
writes  to  the  logfile.   This  bug  seems  to  occur  randomly and isn't
backtraceible.   As  long  as  we  do  not  find  it,  this  feature can be
deactivated  if  the  bug  starts  to  bug  YOU!   :) (Any hints concerning
elimination  of this bug are VERY welcome!  Because it bugs US quite a long
time!  Meanwhile we assume this is a bug in the Arexx-Interpreter itself)

@{u}* Bugfixes:@{uu}

-  Does  not work correctly with Hydracom-MUI V1.8 by MaXiM, because of one
small  difference  to  Olaf  Barthel's Version (just a '/' was missing...).
Fixed.   (But  MUI-Hydra  (1.8)  seems to run unstable in some enviroments,
though...  BTW:  MUI-Hydra 1.9 runs quite stable, but you should not try to
download something from a read-only (namely CD-ROM) media.)

-  Lost-carrier-handling essentially improved.  Now files which are already
uploaded  completely  (and  so are not any longer called BAD-XFER.xxx), are
moved  to  the  Hydra.BAD  Directory  in  the users UUCPdir in case he lost
carrier as well.  When he activates Hydra again, he will be asked wether he
want  to  move  the  files to the Hydra-Temp-directory for including in the
filelisting,  or  to  delete  them  completely.  Note:  credits are handled
absolutely correctly!  No double or non credits for any file.

-  When  a user has uploaded some files via Hydra which still reside in the
Hydra-Temp,  he  will  not be forced to describe the already uploaded files
again.  Same if he changed the the Date via the NEW-Command.


@{u}* New Features:@{uu}

-  Waiting OLMs are now 'deactivated' before processing the uploaded files.
They  will  reappear  after  the  Post-Unit, so nothing will be lost.  OLMs
received while processing may be nuked, though...

-  The number of downloads are increased in the filelist, when this feature
is enabled.  It can take quite a while updating huge filelists, so this is
optional  (feature  was  suggested  and implemented by SI/V\S of Wonderland
BBS,  and slightly optimized by me).  This function will have significantly
more speed if your subboards are RR'ed!

- Files with CDtemp-flag will be copied to "CD-ROM U/D Temp" (as defined in
Config/Path).

-  "File/Byte  credits  to  ULer"  will  now  be set correctly.  This makes
correct "faking" possible again.

-  Check  for  HST-Connects  included.   Hydra  won't  be  useful  with the
HST-Protocol.

-  Replaced    some   DOS-Command-Calls   by   internal   commands  of  the
rexxsupport.lib,  which  weren't documented in the german edition of the C=
Arexx-Reference-book.

-  Put  some  of  the  more important options into an Configuration file on
heavy  demand  by Neurodancer...  =) (I was fed up with changing 'em to fit
MY system -nd)

-  Now  you  may  auto-logoff after transfer if everything is correct.  The
routine acts similar to CNet's build-in, when choosing 'logoff after xfer'.

- Some cosmetical changes...  just look at it!
@endnode

